<Author>SpaceDad
<Content>Very good for the price / Excellent proprietors I stayed at the Hotel Aspen in November of 2006 in order to attend a music function in Amsterdam that lasted through a weekend. I knew I wouldn't be spending too much time at my hotel room, so I wanted something utilitarian (but clean), close to the city center and, yes, not too expensive.The Hotel Aspen fit the bill perfectly and provided a bit more. It's within walking distance (approx. 1 mile) of the Central Rail Station and close to everything in the City Center. The proprietor (unfortunately I didn't write down his name) couldn't have been nicer or more helpful. When I checked in, he immediately provided me with a great walking map of Amsterdam and spent quite a while talking with me about what I wanted to do and the best ways to do it. Both he and his wife treated me extremely well and made me feel right at home.Everything was squeaky clean, including the shared bathroom. I am used to traveling in Europe, so I know that for the price range we are talking about here, you're going to get a tiny room, shared bath, etc. If you want an American-style hotel room, it's going to cost a LOT more than the Aspen, so don't expect luxury. For the single traveller, such as me, who needs a home base from which to enjoy the city, it's perfect.You will probably read a lot about the steep stairs here. It's true, the stairs are well, awesomely steep. However, that's they way it is in almost every building I saw in Amsterdam, and I learned to negotiate them after a short time. I was also travelling quite light - if you have a problem getting around, or are carrying lots of baggage, the stairs might very well be a problem.For the price (Amsterdam is an enormously expensive city, hotel-wise), I can't imagine getting a better deal than the Aspen provided - highly recommended for the practical traveller! 
